<TEXT>
custom officials have seized a truck 
carrying seized steel tubes believed to be parts for a huge iraqi 
gun for firing missiles turkish newspapers reported saturday 
the istanbul daily hurriyet quoted finance and customs minister 
adnan kahveci as saying a massive investigation was under way 
following the seizure 
the tubes discovered wednesday in a truck at kapikule near the 
bulgarian border were sent to the istanbul technical university 
for examination the newspaper said 
on friday greek customs officials seized a huge cylinder that 
it said iraq ordered from britain for an artillery system greeces 
move came seven days after britain also seized a shipment of steel 
tubes headed for iraq 
turkey officials questioned two people in connection with the 
incident but nationalties were not given hurriyet said 
hurriyet said authorities believed the confiscated parts 
resembled those seized in england 
after the greek announcment friday the british company walter 
somers ltd said it had shipped the tubes in two trucks one of 
which had been detained in greece the other in turkey 
istanbul daily cumhuriyet said the british government requested 
the tubes be returned but turkey refused it on grounds of 
international law 
no other details were given in turkish newspapers and officials 
could not immediately be reached to elaborate on saturdays reports 
british officials seized eight steel tubes on the middlesbrough 
docks in england on april 12 the tubes were parts for a gun that 
would be 130 feet long with a bore of nearly 40 inches british 
customs officials said 
the iraqi government and the british manufacturer of the tubes 
sheffield forgemasters have said they were designed for a 
petrochemical plant there was no immediate comment from iraq on 
the greek shipment 
weapons experts have said a gun built from the parts confiscated 
in britain and greece could fire nuclear or chemical missiles 
hundreds of miles far enough to reach israel and iran 
britain banned arms shipments to iran and iraq when the two 
middle eastern countries were at war and the ban remains in effect 
</TEXT>
