beirut radio stations said us hostage 
alann steen is likely to be freed from 39 months of captivity 
sunday on his 51st birthday 
the reports in morning newscasts said steen a boston native 
may be released within a few hours 
speaking on condition of anonymity sources close to the iranian 
embassy told the associated press that steens frail health could 
persuade his kidnappers to end his ordeal steen is held by the 
proiranian islamic jihad for the liberation of palestine 
on saturday staterun beirut television reported proiranian 
kidnappers would turn the freed us hostage over to the us 
ambassador in syria 
in boise idaho the mother of hostage jesse turner said she 
received a call saturday from a state department official saying a 
hostage would be released within 24 to 36 hours 
a department official confirmed the call but said the united 
states was only relaying information given to it by syrian 
officials and had no reason to contradict that information 
beirut televisions englishlanguage news bulletin quoted an 
unidentified syrian official as saying the hostage would be freed 
sometime on sunday probably in the morning by islamic jihad for 
the liberation of palestine 
the hostage will be produced at the syrian foreign ministry 
and then handed over to us ambassador edward djerejian said 
the station which is based in moslem west beirut it did not 
elaborate 
its sister station in christian east beirut later broadcast the 
same report which could not be independently verified 
the reports predicting steens release were broadcast sunday by 
the prestigious moslemrun voice of the nation and the voice of the 
people a communistrun station in west beirut 
voice of the nation said steen will be freed in line with the 
ostentatious behavior of the hostageholders 
steen suffers from chronic high blood pressure in the early 
days of his captivity the kidnappers reported he was gravely ill 
and near death but he appeared on a videotape released in may 1987 
and said he had recovered 
earlier saturday an iranian daily that usually reflects the 
thinking of irans president urged the lebanese kidnappers to keep 
their promise to free an american hostage despite their claim that 
washington was delaying the release 
the tehran times which has repeatedly called for the release of 
all western hostages in lebanon over the last three months said in 
an editorial that the release could be the prelude to the release 
of one more hostage by another group 
daryl penner spokesman for the us embassy in damascus 
stressed saturday that washington will not send john kelly 
assistant secretary of state for near east affairs to negotiate 
the release as demanded by the kidnappers 
syrian foreign ministry sources however said the us embassy 
had requested and been granted permission to land a plane at 
damascus airport 
us embassy officials declined comment but the sources said 
the plane was believed to be to fly a released hostage to 
wiesbaden west germany 
american captives released in the past have been flown to the 
us military hospital there for medical checks and debriefing a 
us team flew there thursday 
turners mother estelle ronneburg said in boise that she was 
called by michael mahoney her liaison with the state department 
she said he did not specify which of the hostages would be 
released turner is one of three us educators held by the 
proiranian group and one of eight americans held in lebanon 
a state department official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
told the associated press that mahoney was relaying information 
given to us officials by the syrian foreign minister mahoney 
told mrs ronnenburg the state department has no information to 
contradict the report according to the official 
white house chief of staff john sununu gave no indication the 
bush administration had any confirmation of a sunday release 
youre always hopeful but having gone through frustrations 
over the years i think everybody involved in this is going to 
believe it only after it happens sununu told cbs news on 
saturday 
the captors said wednesday they would free an american within 48 
hours and they demanded kelly go to damascus to finalize 
arrangements 
but the following day the group declared the release postponed 
indefinitely after president bush citing us policy not to 
negotiate with terrorists refused to send kelly to syria 
the tehran times an englishlanguage daily said in an 
editorial saturday that us ambassador djerejian is good enough 
to conduct the arrangements for the release of the hostage 
djerejian has been involved in frequent talks with syrian officials 
since returning to damascus thursday 
the iranian newspaper which is close to president hashemi 
rafsanjani expressed impatience with the postponement and said it 
hoped the freeing of one captive could be the prelude to the 
release of one more hostage by another group 
it did not specify which proiranian faction it meant by 
another group there are 18 westerners currently held in 
lebanon 
rafsanjani leader of tehrans socalled pragmatists has been 
seeking for months to free the hostages as part of his efforts to 
improve irans relations with the west after a decade of hostility 
he believes that securing the release of hostages will encourage 
western companies to invest in iran to boost its limping economy 
and hopefully encourage washington to release an estimated 12 
billion in frozen assets 
the iranian leader is opposed by fundamentalist antiwestern 
radicals in the tehran hierarchy 
an aide to hussein musawi shiite moslem mentor of islamic jihad 
for the liberation of palestine said saturday that musawi remains 
sure that the group will free one of the americans it holds 
but the aide contacted by telephone by the associated press 
gave no indication when that might be 
musawi heads the shiite islamic amal faction based in the 
syriancontrolled bekaa valley in east lebanon he said friday he 
believed the release will go ahead despite washingtons arrogant 
cowboy behavior 
in addition to turner a communications professor and steen a 
journalism professor the group holds robert polhill 55 an 
accounting lecturer from new york the three were kidnapped from 
the campus of the usaffiliated beirut university college on jan 
24 1987 by gunmen disguised as riot police 
also missing in lebanon are five other americans four britons 
two west germans two swiss an italian and an irishman 
the longestheld captive is terry anderson 42 chief middle 
east correspondent for the associated press he was kidnapped march 
16 1985 and is held by another iranianbacked shiite faction 
islamic jihad or islamic holy war 
