<TEXT>
pope john paul ii on sunday 
called for an unprecedented meeting of european bishops to allow 
the church to keep pace with the political changes sweeping the 
continent 
he made the announcement as he visited a shrine in moravia 
dedicated to cyril and methodius who introduced christianity to 
the slavs 12 centuries ago the old communist regime barred him 
from visiting here in 1985 
john paul said the meeting called a synod will be held at a 
not too distant date 
papal spokesmen joaquin navarro said he did not expect it would 
be held this year he said details will be announced in rome on 
tuesday 
the synod would be the first such continentwide summit bringing 
together bishops from all european countries 
today in this very place we are seeing the signs of a new 
blessing in the promising travail of deep and vital 
transformations said the pope speaking from an altar at a 
700yearold basilica 
he said the european bishops should have the opportunity to 
reflect more on the historic moment for europe and the church 
navarro also announced the pope may visit cuba in december the 
pope had earlier accepted an invitation to visit the caribbean 
island ruled by a hardline communist government but no date had 
been set 
before the mass the pontiff rode through the cobblestone 
streets of velehrad in central czechoslovakia in his white 
popemobile crowds chanted long live the holy father 
as john paul prepared to say mass outside the basilica redone 
in baroque style in the 17th century a huge throng gathered the 
worshipers included polish prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki who 
in august became the east blocs first noncommunist government 
leader 
the czechoslovak news agency ctk estimated the crowd at 200000 
to 400000 
archbishop frantisek vanak of olomouc welcomed john paul to the 
altar the archbishop referred to the popes frustrated attempt to 
visit velehrad in 1985 for a feast to celebrate 1100 years of 
christianity in czechoslovakia 
czechoslovakias leaders who were then communist refused 
permission for the papal visit to this city where cyril and 
methodius introduced christianity to the slavs 
this visit was preceded by years of yearning to have you the 
pope christs witness here among us this yearning was growing 
all the more and more as the dark forces tried to hinder it 
vanak said but gods cause prevailed 
the pope has made the celebration of eastern europes toppling 
of communism a major theme of his twoday trip which began 
saturday it is his first to the region since the dramatic changes 
that rocked communist regimes last year 
until the communist regime fell such a trip was impossible 
but john paul is also warning eastern european countries about 
viruses from the west such as secularism hedonism and atheism 
after celebrating the mass at velehrad the pope was to fly 90 
miles to bratislava the capital of slovakia for another openair 
service 
statistics released by the vatican estimate 107 million 
catholics live in czechoslovakia out of a population of 156 
million 
the pope who turns 70 next month was making the 46th foreign 
pilgrimage of his pontificate 
