talking with health care professionals 
the same fear the same isolation for people with aids the 
same difficulty in mobilizing coordinated care that we saw in the 
beginning of the urban epidemic back a few years ago is happening 
all over again she said 
the commissions trip came on the heels of a federal centers for 
disease control report that aids is spreading more rapidly in rural 
areas than in cities from 1988 to 1989 the cdc found that 
nonmetropolitan areas had a 37 percent increase in new aids cases 
while metro areas had only a 5 percent gain 
in georgia the state department of human resources reported in 
january that the number of aids cases had tripled in two years 
with the rapid spread of the disease in rural parts of the state 
linked to drug users and heterosexual transmission 
rep roy rowland dga a member of the commission agreed with 
