<TEXT>
when 52 american hostages were released by 
iran in 1981 a team of 30 doctors psychiatrists psychologists 
and social workers awaited them in germany to cushion the shock of 
their newly regained freedom 
something similar awaits robert polhill a 55yearold american 
educator who was released sunday by kidnappers in lebanon after 39 
months in captivity this time the assemblage of experts was given 
a name the hostage reception team 
we have procedures in place that ensure that appropriate 
action is taken in the event that a release takes place state 
department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said last week but she 
said detailed discussion of these procedures could complicate an 
already complex and sensitive situation 
the 1981 experience however gives a clue to how the hostage 
reception team works 
the experts were gathered at the us air force hospital in 
wiesbaden west germany members were selected for their experience 
in treating prisoners of war and civilian hostages and a special 
interest in the psychological problems of hostages 
the team members had studied the medical and psychiatric history 
of the hostages before their capture read copies of letters about 
medical matters the hostages had sent form iran and interviewed 
their relatives and physicians 
there was a special circumstance that dictated reading of the 
letters and the interviews the records of those hostages who were 
members of the armed forces were lost when the iranian embassy was 
captured 
with a far greater number of hostages to concern them social 
workers had visited family members to evaluate the psychological 
support the men could expect on their return home others spoke 
with the families by telephone or exchanged letters 
while there is an extensive debriefing process for a hostage 
when he or she is able there is also a briefing process to bring 
the hostage up to date 
experts say when people are taken hostage they are thrust into 
a dependent infantile state they must ask permission to move about 
and take care of physical necessities many hostages respond to 
these indignities by developing trust even gratitude to their 
kidnappers for sparing their lives 
that apparently wasnt the case in 1981 when the hostages had 
been held for 444 days according to doctors the americans were 
treated so badly that they showed no signs of the stockholm 
syndrome which is a gradual bonding of captors and captives the 
name comes from hostages held by trapped robbers in a swedish bank 
many years ago 
one reason hostages are held in wiesbaden for treatment is to 
give them a chance to release tensions and to receive advice on how 
they might deal with potential emotional problems 
