<TEXT>
doctors have saved the life of a baby girl 
born with a fatal heart defect by giving her the heart of her 
braindead twin brother 
the heart was transplanted into alison page whismans chest four 
days after the twins were born on april 10 doctors said sunday 
her doctors said they believe this is the first case of a heart 
transplant between infant twins 
some people have the joy and then experience the sorrow we 
had the sorrow first and now we have our joy said the twins 
father timothy whisman 
page as her parents call her was born one minute before her 
brother tyler he was brain dead asphyxiated in the womb just 
before his birth doctors said 
page appeared strong at delivery but doctors discovered the 
heart defect within 12 hours of her birth 
dr randall caldwell medical director of the riley pediatric 
cardiac transplantation program confirmed that she had hypoplastic 
left heart syndrome a fatal congenital abnormality that occurs in 
about one in 6000 births 
without help infants with the condition die within 15 days 
drugs postpone death for about 45 days 
researchers dont know what causes hypoplastic left heart 
syndrome doctors said the deformity occurs at about four to nine 
weeks after conception when the heart begins forming 
while we at riley did further evaluation of pages cardiac 
status tyler stayed out at humana where they continued the 
neurological work and found out he was indeed brain dead by then 
the parents had been asked that tyler be allowed to donate 
organs caldwell said 
it was the whismans who had the idea for a transplant between 
the twins 
i remember thinking wouldnt it be remarkable if tyler could 
help his little sister said the twins mother paula 
both of our kids were sick poor little tyler with his body 
was brain dead pages only chance was a heart transplant 
whisman said 
the whismans also decided to donate tylers liver to a 
pennsylvania newborn 
page is currently in the newborn intensive care unit she is 
hooked to a heartlung monitor next to her traylike plastic bed 
the whismans have been told that if page continues improving 
they could expect to take her home within three weeks 
</TEXT>
