<TEXT>
premier li peng left monday for the first visit 
in 26 years by a chinese head of government to the soviet union 
chinas longtime rival for leadership of the communist world 
lis fourday trip is intended to promote normal friendly 
relations and an easing of border tensions at a time when both 
countries are focused on serious internal problems 
the official chinese press hailed lis trip as being of 
profound significance to peace in asia and the world but it is 
expected to have few concrete effects on a relationship that has 
slowly improved in recent years after decades of mistrust 
the 61yearold premier is to hold at least two rounds of talks 
with soviet president mikhail s gorbachev who in may made the 
first visit by a soviet leader to beijing in three decades 
gorbachevs historic visit was overshadowed by huge studentled 
democracy demonstrations in beijing which ended weeks later when 
li and other hardline chinese leaders brought in troops to crush 
the movement 
the two sides are expected to sign an agreement on fostering 
trade and will lay down guiding principles on easing military 
confrontation along their 4350mile frontier 
progress is unlikely on territorial disputes or cutbacks in the 
500000 soviet soldiers and more than 1 million chinese troops 
along the border 
china and the soviet union split over ideological differences in 
1960 and fought a brief border war in 1969 in 1972 china restored 
relations with the united states in part because then leader mao 
tsetung saw the soviet union as chinas most serious military 
threat 
western diplomats say improved relations with moscow do not mean 
china can play a soviet card against the united states as 
sinous relations deteriorate over humanrights issues 
china has stressed it will never be a soviet ally as it was in 
the 1950s and chinas inherent suspicions of soviet aims have 
grown with gorbachevs reform policies 
the ideological hardliners who now rule china reportedly blame 
gorbachev for the fall of communist parties in east europe and see 
his program of perestroika as leading to the demise of socialism 
