<DOCNO> AP900422-0088 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the paneuropean stock market is proving an 
elusive dream 
europes major exchanges agree there should be one market in the 
big european stocks to provide greater liquidity and efficiency 
but they disagree over how to create it 
the efforts have been slow piecemeal and contradictory this 
is increasingly helping londons aggressive international stock 
exchange dominate the european financial centers 
europe has 39 national and major regional stock exchanges 
trading about 300 major european stocks 
fragmented structurally diverse they not only compete with 
each other but with less formal trading systems comprised of 
telephone links and computerized videoscreen networks 
moreover they soon will face competition from the national 
association of securities dealers automated quotations also known 
as nasdaq the american screenbased overthecounter market plans 
to begin operating during european hours in the third quarter of 
this year 
the demand for a paneuropean market comes from big 
international institutional investors who want to trade in 
europes stocks in a single market in the european time zone 
andrew hugh smith chairman of londons exchange a year ago 
said the answer was a europewide screenbased trading system 
which london already has 
addressing a conference in frankfurt last month hugh smith 
proposed a joint initiative by london and the german federation of 
stock exchanges as the critical mass the focus upon which a 
truly european market could be built 
regis rousselle head of the paris exchange has suggested 
creating a single european list of 300 major stocks that could be 
traded on any exchange 
the federation of european community stock exchanges meanwhile 
is planning le pipe a system to provide european stock prices 
and company information a single network will transmit data 
prepared by the 12 common market exchanges and it might develop 
into a trading system 
the major investment firms increasingly are engaging in informal 
paneuropean trading through their own computerized videoscreens 
away from the exchanges but this leaves investors less protected 
because theres less surveillance to detect cheating and 
irregularities 
europes exchanges have talked for decades about cooperating 
and it was hoped action would replace words with the approach of 
1992 when the eec theoretically becomes a barrierfree marketplace 
of 320 million consumers 
but stewart gilchrist a director of scottish amicable 
investment managers a glasgowbased institutional investor said 
i dont think we are particularly optimistic 
frank lewis executive director of european trading at shearson 
lehman hutton international inc in london said a paneuropean 
market was an impractical ideal 
every local market is always going to fight to maintain their 
local autonomy and their individuality lewis said theres 
also a hesitancy on the part of the customers 
for instance someone investing in portugal is likely to believe 
that a portuguese broker is the bestqualified to offer advice 
lewis said that is the perception and is to a large degree true 
and can be overcome but its an uphill battle 
londons exchange has used a screenbased system called seaq 
international for five years enabling it to win business from 
other european exchanges and develop substantial trade in 
international shares 
it also benefits from being englishspeaking and better 
established than its continental counterparts 
hugh smith estimated that about onefifth of west german stock 
trading takes place in london where trade in nonbritish shares 
grew to 505 billion in february from 41 billion in september 
london accounted for 35 percent of europes total market 
capitalization of 18 trillion at the end of 1988 figures 
provided by londons exchange show germany came in second with 13 
percent and france third with 115 percent 
the market capitalization figure represents the total value of 
all domestic shares listed on the major exchanges 
west germany is fighting back by modernizing last year it 
launched a screenbased reporting system called ibis which 
provides prices in bluechip stocks to the countrys eight 
exchanges 
one hurdle to harmonization is the wide differences in the way 
the exchanges make the final swap of cash for shares known as the 
clearing and settlement process the exchanges face competition 
from private companies operating as clearing houses 
britains system is among the worst piling up huge backlogs to 
remedy this londons exchange will start operating a paperless 
settlement system called taurus in october 1991 
londons trading is quotedriven with many market makers 
competing for business by offering the best price they have 
abandoned the exchange floor for screens and phones in their 
offices 
but this method has generated such fierce competition that it 
has driven many market makers out of the british equities business 
the sluggish volume following the october 1987 stock market crash 
hasnt helped 
other major exchanges are orderdriven with buyers and 
sellers matched at a central point by market makers known as 
specialists 
their role is similar to that of new york stock exchange 
specialists who are entrusted with the responsibility of keeping 
markets orderly partly through buying and selling shares from 
their own inventories 
the weakness of the continents trading centers became evident 
during the nearcrash last october many of the exchanges shut down 
when they couldnt handle the flood of sell orders 
many european exchanges not london also have circuit 
breakers which limit how far shares can fluctuate in a session 
europes exchanges have scrambled to modernize and deregulate in 
recent years the growth of competition in the 1980s has broken 
down many clubby cartels with their fixed high commissions and 
webs of regulations 
britain led with big bang the sweeping 1986 deregulation 
that allowed foreign firms and commercial banks to deal in 
securities and permitted more participants to make markets in 
stocks 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

